label day_three:

    scene black
    with None

    "When Astrid feeds her the next day, she doesn't ask about Jun's vow from last night. Instead, she busies herself with the mundane. "

    "Jun's best conversations with Astrid before this were created by stoking her temper. There was only so much thinking and monologuing she could do all on her lonesome before she went insane. Astrid, while undoubtedly hostile, gave her the variety she needed."

    "Whatever favor she had earned last night had transformed Astrid entirely, with her curiosity focusing less and less on what Jun was, but rather who. "

    a "I never understood your… distaste for animal blood. "

    j "You'd prefer a more flavorful steak over a bland one. I don't see how it's any different."

    a "Is there even a difference in flavor? I'd assume that most blood would have a similar flavor palate."

    j "Humans have a richness to their blood that I can't find in other animals. Some are.. nice, but I still prefer human blood. "

    j "But not just any human will do, mind you. Healthy ones who aren't diseased and halfway through death's door."

    a "You could easily make yourself a close substitute with animal blood depending on what you feed them."

    a "Back when I was staying with the tribe, I was forced to find ways to feed myself that didn't involve human flesh due to the scarcity of them in the area. Usually, when I was hungry, a dissenter was thrown for me to feast on."

    a "Still, I was taught that you could find decent substitutes for humans in things like pork and beef if they were fed the right nutrients. "

    j "You can, but again, it pales in comparison to the real thing. Everyone acts like it's a luxury now, but it's really not if you have the power and brains for it."

    j "And that is interesting. Cannibalism is frowned on in most species. Your tribe is strange."

    a "Not my tribe."

    "She interjects, a little too eager to clarify the error."

    j "Of course, of course."

    a "And besides, does it truly count as cannibalism? "

    a "If we were to play with the hypothetical, wouldn't you be participating in the same sin?"

    a "Humans and vampires aren't too different in genetic makeup, after all."

    j "Would you say that to an elf? Just because we have similar features in certain areas doesn't mean we're the same. Are dogs the same as you wolves?"

    a "Elves don't feed on humans."

    j "Some do. "

    j "It's really not that hard to achieve. They're exceedingly fragile."

    a "I… did not know that, actually. Where did you hear of such elves?"

    "Jun laughs."

    j "It's not just elves, either. Cults that kill and eat humans aren't an original premise nowadays."

    a "Barbaric, honestly."

    j "Hah! Human sympathizer."

    j "Or are they your type? Have pretty elf girls finally been overthrown as the main crush of most species?"

    a "It is merely the right choice."

    a "If the chosen species were, say, elves, the Highmother would not dedicate herself to humans so diligently. She knows there is innate value in the human race."

    a "Besides, you must admire their resourcefulness and tenacity when compared to the other races. "

    a "Dwarves have enhanced natural strength, Elves have a higher connection to magic. Humans? They are thrust upon a world unkind to them, and yet they are able to survive and conquer with mere wit."

    "Jun considers the rather sound argument and weighs whether or not to reply with a sound argument of her own."

    j "So you are into human girls."

    "She chooses the more interesting option."

    a "…You could say so, yes."

    j "Aha! I knew it. "

    j "Seems that Highmother of yours has you loyal in more ways than one~"

    a "…"

    j "What? It was obvious. "

    a "…Eat your meal."

    j "Fine. I'll leave you alone."

    j "There has to be at least one annoying human you've met, though."

    a "There isn't one. Their behavior is usually quite warranted considering my unsavory origins."

    j "I don't believe you. You're so sensitive even when I'm just asking you questions. You have to have gotten angry at some point."

    a "I get ‘sensitive' at you because you're a prisoner. They are my superiors. It's fair to expect patience and obedience from a lesser being. That's the nature of a conquering species."

    j "So gloomy. Is there anything that makes you happy in this place?"

    j "Your job doesn't count."

    a "Why doesn't it? It is my passion, my purpose. Of course I'd find fulfillment and happiness in it."

    j "I mean something you do for fun even if you don't have to. Mahjong, fencing, styling your hair?"

    a "…Working on the farm during my banishment was calming. Or will you be telling me that doesn't count."

    j "A farm! How cute. I've never really seen one, so I wouldn't know anything about it. Castles are more my style."

    j "Tell me what you like about it and I'll decide."

    a "…The serenity, I suppose. The gentle sway of the grass, the cool breeze blowing past my face."

    a "The monotony of the tasks, if that makes any sense."

    a "It felt… nice. As painful as it is to be away from home, to be away from Her, it was… somewhat comforting. "

    a "To be alone, to be unbothered and not be reminded near constantly of my own blasphemy."

    a "A blasphemous existence I never even chose."

    "Against her own better judgement, a bit of guilt began to fester within Jun. "

    "She pushes it down immediately. The benefit of what she would surely reap if she kept it going just a little longer outweighed anything else."

    "Someone else could be the hero, breaking down all of her walls and reaching for the scared little girl within."

    "Jun needed a beast."

    # fade black

    "They keep talking for so long that Jun sees a human for the first time in a while. They bark an order that has Astrid scurrying out without so much as a goodbye. Jun glares so intensely at them that they leave in much the same fashion."

    "In spite of her hunger, her food feels a lot less appealing now."

    "She opts to rest in the time Astrid is away. The hours stretch uncomfortably long in her absence. "

    "Oddly enough, she misses their talks, even if they reveal just how sheltered and inexperienced Astrid is in just about anything that isn't servitude and survival. She looks forward to Astrid's return, and prays her punishment isn't too severe."

    "She dreams again of wandering hands and thatch-roofed cottages. "

    "Jun gets her wish soon enough, the door creaking open to signal Astrid's return. It's late enough that any discussion she wanted to have would surely eat into her resting hours, but she figures she can make up for that just fine with some naps in the morning."

    "It seems like a nice night, too. "

    "A pretty tune floats in the air, a chorus of voices melding together in perfect harmony. If she shuts her eyes, she can imagine they are singing just for her."

    "However, Astrid's face looks incredibly sullen, even more so than usual, giving her pause. Her hands squeeze at the battleaxe in her grip, looking away, as if ashamed of what's to come."

    "She can't even face her."

    a "…It's time."

    "She feels her chest constrict."

    "She always knew, distantly, that the day would come. In the latter half of her confinement here, she thought she had grown to accept it. "

    "Now, she is a lamb with shaky limbs, a child tugging at her mother's skirt and crying no, please, I don't want to go! "

    "Her days can't be over, dreams spilling over onto childhood diaries and wistful missives screamed to be let free. "

    "She wants to see her friends again, travel the world, fall in love. She wants, wants, wants but fact refuses to budge to accommodate her."

    "Seized by frenzy, she thrashes about. Her chains don't give. The magic pulsing through them renders her powerless."

    "Fear shoots through her, a lance in her heart. All Astrid can do is stare in disappointment."

    a "Jun."

    "Every waking moment has been uncomfortable and cold and full of ache, but she knows in this instant that she would take a hundred more than let it end here."

    a "Jun."

    "She is Jun Yue, goddammit. She has always had her way. Why does it have to stop now?"

    j "Please, no."

    "Her voice cracks. Tears trickle, unbidden, down her cheeks. Whatever strength she had held onto was nothing in the face of the toll of her end drawing near."

    j "I'm scared. I don't want to."

    "Astrid steps closer. Consequently, Jun flinches away, pressing herself up against the wall. Every part of her is screaming to run, but she has nowhere to go here."

    "Not under Astrid's watchful eye."

    a "It is only a matter of time before your judgement, Jun Yue. Only you get to decide if you wish to leave the world doing what's right, or remaining a stain on what could be a blemishless world. "

    j "Please don't make me do it. I'll leave this village alone. I won't eat humans anymore."

    a "Your sins can no longer be forgiven. It is only what you do after that can give you the slightest mercy from the wrath of those above. "

    j "Please, Astrid-"

    a "Your family's location, Jun. "

    "She sobs. "

    "Astrid grabs against the bars of her cage. "

    a "Their location, Jun. You said you would tell me."

    a "I believe there is still hope for your soul, no matter what you've done before. Give yourself the one chance you have for redemption. Tell me where they are."

    "She can hardly speak. Opening her mouth causes another wail to tumble out. She doesn't want to die. She doesn't want to die."

    a "You cannot go back on your word now. What happened to the strength and glory you preached to me? You're faced with the final thing you could do to make any of the self-aggrandizing you do mean anything, and all you do is weep?"

    "Her breathing is ragged and frantic. The beautiful melody serenading her earlier warps into something ominous and discordant. There would be no lullabies rocking her motionless body to an early grave. "

    a "JUN."

    "A slam at the bars, a grasp of her battleaxe. She glares at Jun, devoid of the previous warmth she had seen so much of today."

    a "Give me what I'm asking for, or I'll have no choice but to make you."

    "The walls are closing in on her. She curls herself into a tiny ball, eyes squeezed shut. Her heart is a jackhammer in her ribcage. "

    "Astrid sighs. Her hand lets go of the metal, the squeak of her boots and the screech of her axe is all that echoes through the room."

    "A turn of the knob and Astrid is inside, a few inches away from her newest prey. "

    "Step, step, step. "

    "The screeching and stepping rings closer and closer and closer until she feels Astrid's hand yanking at her hair, lifting her up from her protective position."

    "She is sure that Astrid would have done more, if not for the sound of the bells ringing. "

    a "…Come on. The Highmother awaits."

label day_three_cont:

    "The rattle of her chain cuts through the eerie choir with a strange, syncopated beat. They walk down a seemingly endless hall, Jun keeping her vision fixed squarely to the floor. "

    "She can see the back of Astrid's shoes, a steady march towards her undoing."

    "It is a rhythm that, much like time, can only keep marching forward. "

    "She does not falter."

    "As Jun drags her feet on the uneven stone, she experiences an inkling of familiarity. "

    "Surveying her surroundings, a memory makes its way back to the forefront of her consciousness."

    "It was this exact passage that connected the town to the rest of the outside world. "

    "She had observed it from afar in the dead of night while snatching reckless humans venturing too far outside the sanctity of their settlement, and she had seen it up close when she was escorted to her place of imprisonment. "

    "Just beyond the passage was the town's High Altar, a hulking megalith carved from the base of the mountain the village sat atop. Lining the edge of the altar itself were runes not dissimilar to the ones carved in her cell, or pressed into the metal of her cuffs. "

    "A few inches away from the opening, Astrid stops dead in her tracks and looks her in the eye for the first time since they started their walk."

    "Lifting her head while caressing her cheek with her thumb, she coos, softened now that Jun's hysterics had dwindled to a solemn resignation."

    a "…It's alright, Jun. "

    a "You don't need to fear it. I'll be there with you. "

    "With a tug, Astrid drags her face closer and closer, until they're a hairsbreadth apart. "

    "Their lips press together, and a shock goes through her body. She is helpless to resist. Astrid's touch travels down, down, down. Running careful fingers against her side, squeezing against soft and yielding skin."

    "She had spent her whole life fighting the delusion that love could be anything kind. It was easier to believe violence was the only way to profess devotion, but the sheer care and gentleness of Astrid's callused, battle-worn hands makes her crave more."

    "Her mind is spinning, the choir's song fading away into nothing but noise, giving way for Astrid's voice and her voice alone to move through her ears."

    a "You've had to fight for so long, haven't you?"

    "Why give her this now, when there's no hope? When she'd stopped fighting?"

    "Was this all her life was cracked up to be? Toyed with and at the mercy of another?"

    "If she had given in sooner, would she have found the love she had always wanted?"

    a "You won't have to fight so hard anymore. I'll love you, Jun~"

    "Maybe in death she would reach a serenity she had seldom allowed herself in life."

    "Astrid would be with her for the rest of her time. Astrid would love her for as long as she lived. Astrid believed she could be perfect. "

    "Astrid, Astrid, Astrid-"

    a "We both will be worth the Highmother's love soon enough."

    ".."

    "What?"

    "What more could she possibly offer? "

    "A life spent being second rate, chasing an idea of who she could be and coming up short. A flash in the pan, a one hit wonder. Ridiculed, demeaned, and molded into a callous, unfeeling thing."

    "Friends move to greater heights as you remain rooted to the ground, and plans fall apart. Now this: prison cells and empty stomachs and no move, move, move to keep you quiet and muzzled. Tear into yourself because there's no more hiding behind stronger fronts."

    "A taste of normalcy. "

    "Flowers in full bloom in a humble garden, now complete with promise rings and lazy days."

    "What if the cabin was a cottage was a farm and it was made for two just us two together forever and ever?"

    "I love you."

    "I hate you."

    "You made me do this."

    ".."

    "I'm sorry, mama."

    a "gHK-"

    "It's divine."

    "Ambrosia on her tongue, sweet nectar from the vine."

    "She wasn't prepared for it. How could she be?"

    "Jun is on her in an instant. She is greedy and thirsty and Astrid is splayed out before her like a banquet."

    "It hits her like a drug, parting flesh from flesh, stained in the color of another. "

    "Red, so red."

    "Astrid is beautiful."

    "Breast heaving with labored breaths, twitching like a fish out of water. "

    "She licks her lips just to savor the taste."

    "…"

    "The key isn't hard to get ahold of. The well placed bite bought Jun precious time to wrestle it away and take off her cuffs. They clatter to the ground uselessly."

    "Free from her shackles, she kneels to Astrid's level."

    j "If being a martyr suits you well enough, then be my guest, but the only thing that separates a shepherd's dog from a wolf is what side of the fence they're on."

    j "I hope you can choose to be free."

    j "Goodbye, Astrid."

